Estimating the number of off grid households

Scotland

Ben Anderson (b.anderson@soton.ac.uk @dataknut)

Last run at: 2020-03-26 12:29:13

1 About

Circulation:

1.1 Purpose

This report is intended to:

  • estimate the number of off-grid households in Scotland;
  • with a specific focus on the Highlands & Islands

This work was carried out by the Sustainable Energy Research Group in the University of Southamptons Faculty of Engineering and Environment.

2 Introduction

It started with a tweet:

  • https://twitter.com/hannon_matthew/status/1242790919818153984

3 Data used

  • Census 2011 data on the number of household spaces for Scotland at datazone level;
  • BEIS 2010 - 2018 data on the number of electricty meters at datazone level.

4 Method

If we assume:

  • the number of household spaces off grid = n household spaces - n meters

Then in theory we can estimate the number who are off grid. Of course some may be off grid but still have a meter. And it is crucial that we have an accurate estimate of the number of household spaces to match to the BEIS data. Of course we only have that at datazone level for 2011as we will see.

5 Results

This should be the most accurate year as the data sources match.

6 Conclusion

Dont you hate it when a good idea goes belly-up.

Suggestions: * try aggregating everything to higher zone levels? But given the errors we see here even in 2011, why would that help?
